Organisms should move without regard for the state of non-organism-live-grid-cells.

It is vital to keep live-non-organism cells out of an organism's cytoplasm, as this
pollutes the organism's living "DNA" and causes it to grow out of control.

At several stages of a tick, non-organism-live-grid-cells may potentially overlap 
organism skin and cytoplasm cells.

When that overlap happens, has happened, or is about to happen, the organism will "eat" those cells and 
they will immediately die. This behavior writ large is called "Grazing."

The Organism will track how many cells it has eaten and display that statistic in the 
Community Selection panel.

These instructions reiterate existing collision avoidance instructions. 
Collision avoidance logic should NOT be changed, but GRAZING and ISOLATION support should be added 
at each stage as follows:

1. BEFORE TICK (OrganismManager):
    - Take a snapshot of the organism's legitimate DNA cells (The "ROSTER").
    - Silently clear the organism's own DNA from the grid.
    - Graze: Eat any non-roster live cells within the skin and cytoplasm.
2. ON TICK (SimulationContext / Grid3D):
    - Prevent GOL births inside the organism's "Forbidden Zone" (DNA + Cytoplasm + Skin).
    - This ensures that when ORGANISM SUPPORT is OFF, the simulation performs in its original fashion.
3. AFTER TICK (processOrganisms):
    - Sequence: Juke/Rotate -> Sanitization -> Isolated GOL -> Post-GOL Grazing.
    - Movement Grazing: Preemptively eat non-organism cells in the Juke/Rotate paths.
    - PRE-GOL SANITIZATION:
        - Re-compute fresh Roster/Cytoplasm/Skin for the resolved (post-movement) position.
        - THE SKIN MUST BE DEVOID OF LIVING CELLS (Eat ALL non-organism live cells in skin).
        - Eat any non-roster live cells in the cytoplasm.
    - ISOLATED GOL:
        - Apply 3D-GOL rules ONLY among the organism's current roster and its own cytoplasm.
        - EXTERNAL neighbors (non-organism cells) must NOT be counted in the organism's survival/birth logic.
    - POST-GOL FILTERING:
        - Keep only the SINGLE LARGEST connected component (≥3 cells). Discard smaller fragments.
    - POST-GOL 2-CELL GRAZING:
        - Re-compute final Roster from the GOL result.
        - Eat any live non-roster cell WITHIN 2 CELLS of any cell in the new roster.
    - RECONSTITUTE:
        - Rebuild the permanent cytoplasm and skin around the final new roster.
